ire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Dunblane, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dunblane, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda Gillebrigte was born about 1225 as the daughter of Gilbert Gilchrist. She married Malise 5th Earl of Strathearn before 12 December 1257. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1267, at the age of 43, and was buried in Dunblane, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1225–BY 1267":"umbes 1225–1267","1225–1267":"12